Travel Guide

Getting to Bodrum
+
Airport

Milas–Bodrum International Airport (BJV) is the best airport to fly into (around 40 minutes from the resort).

International Flights

There are lots of direct international flights to Istanbul and Bodrum, as well as plenty of connecting options via Europe and the Middle East. If you're travelling from London, it can sometimes be easier to book separate one-way flights for more choice.

Where possible, we recommend flying straight into Bodrum. If there isn't a direct flight, the simplest route is usually via Istanbul.

Domestic Flights

Common options include Turkish Airlines, Pegasus Airlines, and AJet.

Baggage allowances on domestic flights within Türkiye are often lower than international flights, so add extra baggage when you book if needed.

Visas
  • UK, Canada & USA passport holders do not need a visa for short stays
  • Indian passport holders will need a visa arranged in advance (no visa on arrival)
  • You may be eligible for an e-Visa if you hold a valid Schengen, UK, or US visa

All travellers should ensure their passport has at least 6 months' validity remaining from the date of travel.

Istanbul

Istanbul: 1. Historical Peninsula
+
Must See
  • Hagia Sophia (must see)
  • Blue Mosque (must see)
  • Basilica Cistern (must see)
  • Suleymaniye Mosque (amazing mosque, a bit out of the way, but worth it)
  • Topkapı Palace / Museum (if you have at least few hours, worth it)
  • Grand Bazaar & Egyptian Bazaar
  • Hamams: There are lots of hamams in the area if it's of interest for someone
Eats Nearby
  • Balık Ekmek: Fish Sandwich, Streetfood: Eminönü (close to Historical peninsula)
  • Olden 1772: Cool restaurant in the area
  • Pandeli Restaurant: Traditional Turkish food
Istanbul: 2. Taksim, Beyoğlu, Karaköy
+
Highlights
  • Istiklal Street: Walking through the street from Istiklal Square to Beyoglu; shops, churches and some passageways in it
  • Galata Tower: Instead of going up on the tower, there are a lot of restaurants that would have the same view just by it
  • Art Museums: Istanbul Modern, Pera Museum, SALT Galata
Restaurants
  • Biz İstanbul: Amazing view, modern take on traditional Turkish cuisine
  • Okra İstanbul: Amazing view, fine dining
  • Mürver Restaurant
  • Mükellef Karaköy
  • GalataPort: Port/mall with restaurants in it by Bosphorus
Istanbul: 3. Bosphorus Coast & Rumeli Fortress
+
The Experience

All the way from Tarabya to Karaköy, by the water, is great. On a good day, you can walk any part of it.

Arnavutköy

Kind of in the middle of this path. Good for seafood and nice views; close to Rumeli Fortress.

Bebek to Tarabya

For people that has more time, I highly recommend visiting this stretch by the sea: very peaceful, amazing views and nice walks.

Istanbul: 4. Kadıköy-Moda
+
The Vibe

Hip, young neighbourhood with lots of shops, coffee shops, music venues on the Anatolian-side.

Tip

It's worth taking the ferry from Beşiktaş or Karaköy to Kadıköy and back. It's cheap and totally worth it, amazing view and experience.

Istanbul: 5. Beşiktaş: Dolmabahçe Palace
+
What's There

Lots of shops and historical places such as Dolmabahçe Palace.

Note: Because Beşiktaş is more of a local square to commute, it can get a bit chaotic time to time.

Istanbul: What to Eat
+
Turkish Kebap

We have many different types and it's a bit different than what "kebab" is in Europe. The classic would be Adana Kebap (spicy) or Urfa Kebap (not spicy Adana Kebap). In a good restaurant, I recommend a "plate." In more of a casual spot, you can get it in dürüm (wrapped) version.

Döner

Same as kebap, slightly different than what is döner in Europe. In a good restaurant, I highly recommend a plate or even Iskender (döner plate with special tomato-sauce and butter). In casual spots, you can get a wrap or sandwich versions as well.

Turkish Delight

Ali Muhiddin Hacibekir (Best and one of the only traditional Turkish delight shops, family-owned and operated since the year 1777). They have locations in Eminönü, Taksim, Kadıköy. I highly recommend not buying Turkish delight anywhere else, especially grand bazaar or Istiklal Street.

Lahmacun & Pide

Turkish style meat-pie and Turkish style flatbread.

Seafood

Türkiye have a massive list of seafood available. I highly recommend going to a nice restaurant, with a nice view just by the sea, and trying different fish. Whatever is in season, go for it as a big fish. It's always good to support it with small mezes (appetizer plates which they'll have many of them) & calamari.

Desserts

Baklava (Try in Güllüoğlu, one of the few traditional ones left in touristic areas: classic one is the pistachio one), Künefe, Sütlaç.

For Foodies

Streetfood of Istanbul: Börek (Flaky pastry with cheese, spinach, or meat), Kokorec (intestines), Islak hamburger (wet burger), balık ekmek (fish sandwich), midye dolma (stuffed mussels), Kumpir (baked potato with toppings).

Regional Kebap Types: Some that are more of regional delights that you might come across in Istanbul: Cağ Kebabı, Testi Kebabı, Tas Kebabı.

Home Cooking: Some of the food that's prepared in most Turkish houses: Mantı, Sarma, İçli Köfte, Karnıyarık, Hünkar Beğendi, Dolma, Kuru fasulye.

Bodrum

Bodrum Highlights
+
The essentials

Bodrum Castle + marina walk. Old Town for an easy evening stroll.

The best Bodrum day

Boat trip. Swim in hidden coves. Repeat.

Sunset spots

Gümüşlük (laid-back harbour) or Yalıkavak (polished marina + dinner).

A little myth for you

Bodrum was once Halicarnassus—home to a spring called Salmakis. According to Ovid, the water nymph Salmacis fell for Hermaphroditus and clung to him in the water, praying they'd never be separated. The gods listened. They became one being. Ancient writers said anyone who drank from the spring would be "softened" by its magic.
